<div class="content">
<h2> Creating lexically scoped functions in newLISP </h2>
A default function looks and behaves similar to statically scoped functions found in other programming languages. Several functions can share one namespace.<br>
<br>
Using the built-in primitive <tt>def-new</tt>, a function or macro can be defined to create other functions enclosed in their own namespace:<br>
<br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;(define&nbsp;(def-static&nbsp;s&nbsp;body)&nbsp;</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(def-new&nbsp;'body&nbsp;(sym&nbsp;s&nbsp;s)))&nbsp;</tt><br>
<br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;(setq&nbsp;sum&nbsp;0)</tt><br>
<br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;(def-static&nbsp;'acc&nbsp;(lambda&nbsp;(x)</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(inc&nbsp;sum&nbsp;x)))</tt><br>
<br>
<br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;(acc&nbsp;5)&nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;5</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;(acc&nbsp;5)&nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;10</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;(acc&nbsp;2)&nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;12</tt><br>
<tt></tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;acc:sum&nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;12</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;acc:x&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;nil</tt><br>
<br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;acc:acc&nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;(lambda&nbsp;(acc:x)&nbsp;(inc&nbsp;acc:sum&nbsp;acc:x))</tt><br>
<br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;sum&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;0</tt><br>
<br>
The function works by creating a context and <em>default functor</em> from the name of the function. The value of <tt>acc:sum</tt> is initialized to <tt>0</tt> copying the value of <tt>MAIN:sum</tt>.<br>
<br>
Using <tt>acc</tt> as a prototype, new statically scoped functions can be created:<br>
<br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;(new&nbsp;'acc&nbsp;'myacc)</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;(myacc&nbsp;3)&nbsp;→&nbsp;15</tt><br>
<br>
The new function will start of with <tt>myacc:sum</tt> as present in <tt>acc:sum</tt>
when doing the copy with <tt>new</tt>.<br>
<br>
Using a more complex method, a <tt>def-static</tt> can be defined as a macro which can be used like the normal define function:<br>
<br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;;;&nbsp;define&nbsp;static&nbsp;functions&nbsp;(use&nbsp;only&nbsp;in&nbsp;context&nbsp;MAIN)</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;;;</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;;;&nbsp;Example:</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;;;</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;;;&nbsp;(def-static&nbsp;(foo&nbsp;x)&nbsp;(+&nbsp;x&nbsp;x))</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;;;</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;;;&nbsp;foo:foo&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;(lambda&nbsp;(foo:x)&nbsp;(+&nbsp;foo:x&nbsp;foo:x))</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;;;</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;;;&nbsp;(foo&nbsp;10)&nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;20</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;;;</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;(define-macro&nbsp;(def-static)</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(let&nbsp;(temp&nbsp;(append&nbsp;(lambda)&nbsp;(list&nbsp;(1&nbsp;(args&nbsp;0))&nbsp;(args&nbsp;1))))</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(def-new&nbsp;'temp&nbsp;(sym&nbsp;(args&nbsp;0&nbsp;0)&nbsp;(args&nbsp;0&nbsp;0)))))</tt><br>
<br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;(def-static&nbsp;(acc&nbsp;x)</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(inc&nbsp;sum&nbsp;x))</tt><br>
<br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;(acc&nbsp;5)&nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;5</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;(acc&nbsp;5)&nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;10</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;(acc&nbsp;2)&nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;12</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;acc:sum&nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;12</tt><br>
<tt>&nbsp;&nbsp;acc:x&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;nil</tt><br>
<br>
The macro <tt>def-static</tt> first creates a lambda expression of the function to be defined in the current name space and assigns it to the variable <tt>temp</tt>. In a second step the lambda function in <tt>temp</tt> is copied to its own name space. This happens by assigning it to the default functor <tt>acc:acc</tt> symbol built from the name of the function.<br>

